Methods:
Animals
All animal procedures were approved by the Institutional Animal Care and Use Committee of the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign. GnRH-Cre females and males (Jackson Labs #021207) on the C57BL/6J background were housed in a 14:10 h light:dark cycle (lights off at 1900 h) with food and water available
ad libitum
. The animals used in this study were progeny not used in breeding pairs for ongoing projects that require Cre expression in GnRH neurons (
Ingram et al., 2022
;
Li et al., 2018
;
Li and Christian-Hinman, 2022
). After weaning, all animals were group-housed with two to five mice per cage. Estrous cycle monitoring was performed from 0900 to 1100h as previously described starting at postnatal day (P) 42 (
Pantier et al., 2019
). Daily cycle stage monitoring was done for at least 2 weeks prior to intrahippocampal injection to ensure that all animals entered in the study had normal estrous cycles. From 14-17 days prior to initial tail blood sampling, the cycle stages in each mouse were monitored again to determine if post-injection estrous cycle disruption had occurred. The cycle length was calculated as the time it took on average to progress from one day of estrus through each stage to the next day of estrus (
Li et al., 2018
,
2017
). IHKA mice that had cycle lengths of seven days or more were categorized as “IHKA-long”, while those that maintained a normal cycle length (4-6 days) were categorized “IHKA-regular” (
Li et al., 2018
,
2017
). All control animals maintained regular estrous cycle lengths following intrahippocampal saline injection.

Intrahippocampal kainic acid injection and EEG electrode implantation
All surgical procedures were conducted under isoflurane inhalation anesthesia. At P56 and older, mice underwent unilateral injection of kainic acid (Tocris Bioscience; 50 nl, 20 mM prepared in 0.9% sterile saline) into the right dorsal hippocampal region to elicit chronic recurrent seizure development (from Bregma: 2.0 mm posterior, 1.5 mm lateral, 1.4 mm ventral to the cortical surface). All injections in females were performed on diestrus. Each mouse was randomly assigned to IHKA or saline injection. Injections were performed by lab personnel not involved in the data collection or analysis process. Controls were injected with the same volume of saline at the same location. To record the incidence of seizures, 14 days after injection the mice were implanted with twisted bipolar EEG electrodes (P1 Technologies) into the ipsilateral hippocampus (
Armstrong et al., 2013
;
Cutia et al., 2022
;
Li et al., 2020
;
Li and Christian-Hinman, 2022
). Implantation was slightly dorsal and lateral to the injection location (from Bregma: 1.75 mm lateral, 1.25 mm ventral). Five anchor micro-screws (J.I. Morris Co.) were then inserted into and distributed across the frontal, parietal, and occipital skull plates. The electrode and screws were stabilized to the skull surface with dental cement (Teets “Cold Cure” Dental Cement). Each mouse was a single experimental unit and was singly housed after EEG instrumentation to avoid damage to the implant.

EEG recording and analysis
7 days after EEG electrode implantation, the mice were singly housed and tethered to an electrical commutator (P1 Technologies). The mice were habituated to tethering for five weeks prior to experimentation to avoid tethering-induced disruption to the estrous cycle (
Li et al., 2020
). 24 hours prior to initial tail blood sampling, the commutator was connected to a Brownlee 440 amplifier (NeuroPhase) with the gain set at 1K to collect EEG signals recorded as the local field potential differential between the two electrodes (
Armstrong et al., 2013
). These signals were sampled at 2 kHz and digitized to a computer with recorder software written in MATLAB (
Armstrong et al., 2013
). At 2 months post-injection, the mice were recorded for 9-24 hours prior to tail blood sampling (
Li and Christian-Hinman, 2022
) and through the 3-hour sampling period. Recordings were analyzed with an automated electrographic seizure analyzer (
Zeidler et al., 2018
), with the minimal seizure duration set at five seconds and interictal interval set at six seconds. Experimenters were blinded to the injection group of the animal during analysis.

Tail blood sampling and trunk blood collection
Beginning 14 days prior to initial tail blood sampling, mice underwent daily tail touch habituation in which the tail was stroked six times every five minutes for 15 minutes (
McCosh et al., 2018
). This habituation is necessary to reduce stress, which can affect LH release (
Yang et al., 2018
). Mice were sampled twice at approximately 2 months after intrahippocampal injection: once on a day in diestrus and once on a day in estrus. The sampling order of mice on diestrus or estrus was counterbalanced to ensure equal numbers of animals underwent first sampling at each cycle stage. On the day of sampling, <1 mm of the tail tip was clipped off and 6 μl of blood was pipetted off the tail using pipette tips prewashed in EDTA (
Steyn et al., 2013
). Blood samples were collected every five minutes for three hours, with every other sample collected (i.e., samples collected every 10 minutes) subjected to final LH assays. Samples were collected with minimal restraint of the mouse between 0800 h and 1200 h. The blood samples were diluted in 54 μl of buffer (prepared as 0.5 g BSA and 125 μl Tween 20 in 250 mL of 1X PBS) and stored on ice. Mice were returned to their home cage between sample collections. At the end of the 3-hour period of LH sampling, a 150 ng/kg bolus intraperitoneal (IP) injection of GnRH (Bachem 4033013; LHRH acetate salt prepared in 0.9% sterile saline) was administered (“GnRH challenge”) (
Czieselsky et al., 2016
;
Han et al., 2015
;
Silveira et al., 2017
). 15 minutes after this injection, a final tail blood collection was made. Once all samples for a given session were collected, mice were allowed to recover for at least 7 days before further sampling or experimentation. Blood samples were stored at −20°C before being assayed. Experimenters were blinded to the injection group of each animal during sampling.
Trunk blood, collected at the time of euthanasia via decapitation at least one week after the last blood sampling period, was stored at 4°C overnight, and following centrifugation serum was collected for FSH assays. Sample collection from females was conducted on a day of estrus or diestrus, assigned randomly to each mouse.

Measurement of blood LH and FSH levels
LH and FSH concentrations were measured by the University of Virginia Ligand Assay and Analysis Core using ultrasensitive enzyme-linked immunosorbent assays (ELISAs) for mouse LH in whole blood (
Steyn et al., 2013
) and for mouse FSH in serum (
Ongaro et al., 2021
). The reportable range for the LH assays was 0.16 - 40.0 ng/ml. All % CV values for LH assays were < 10. The reportable range for the FSH assay was 0.16 - 80.0 ng/ml. The % CV value for the FSH assay was 3.4.

Pituitary qPCR
Pituitaries were removed at the time of euthanasia and stored in RNAlater (Invitrogen) at −20°C. RNAqueous-Micro kits (Invitrogen) were used to isolate pituitary RNA. The ProtoScript First Strand cDNA Synthesis kit (New England Biolabs) was then used to reverse transcribe the total RNA (
Cutia et al., 2022
;
Nantie et al., 2014
). Oligonucleotide primers for the GnRH receptor (
Gnrhr
) (Life Technologies) gene were used to amplify gene-specific transcripts by quantitative PCR (qPCR). mRNA expression levels of Peptidylprolyl isomerase A (
Ppia
), a common reference gene used as an internal control, were used to normalize the expression levels of the gene of interest. The data were analyzed using the standard comparative cycle threshold value method (2
−ΔΔCt
).

Evaluation of LH pulse parameters
LH peaks and pulse dynamics were quantified in a blinded manner. LH concentration values that showed at least a 20% increase from prior points and were followed by an immediate decrease of at least 10% were characterized as pulse peaks as previously described (
Esparza et al., 2020
;
Yang et al., 2018
). All other parameters (amplitude, basal levels, and mean release) were calculated for each mouse using established standards (
Esparza et al., 2020
;
Yang et al., 2018
). Specifically, LH pulse amplitude was calculated as the difference between the concentration of an LH peak and the trough (lowest value) immediately preceding the peak. Basal LH was defined as the average of all LH samples not identified as peak points of release, and mean LH was defined as the average LH concentration across all samples. Interpulse interval was defined as the time between two successive peaks.

Statistics
Basal, mean, and pulse amplitude measures of LH, post-GnRH challenge differences, and FSH levels were compared between IHKA-long, IHKA-regular, and saline-injected control mice on both diestrus and estrus using one-way ANOVAs. Tukey’s
post hoc
tests were used for further pairwise comparisons. Interpulse interval values were compared between saline/IHKA females on diestrus and estrus using Kruskal-Wallis tests. All comparisons of LH pulse parameters, post-GnRH challenge differences, and FSH levels in males were conducted using two-sample t-tests. Comparisons of percent change between diestrus and estrus for LH pulse parameters and post-GnRH challenge differences were conducted using Kruskal-Wallis tests. Diestrus-to-estrus repeated measures comparisons of LH parameters and post-GnRH challenge differences within each group of females were made using paired t-tests. Comparisons between saline/IHKA males and diestrous females for LH pulse parameters, post-GnRH challenge differences, and FSH levels were made using two-way ANOVAs and Tukey’s
post hoc
tests. Comparison of
Gnrhr
mRNA expression between saline and IHKA females was made using a Wilcoxon rank sum test. Normality was evaluated with Shapiro-Wilks tests and homogeneity of variance was assessed with Levene’s tests. Pearson’s correlations were used to compare percent time spent in seizures and LH pulse parameters. All statistical analyses were conducted using R in RStudio. Statistical significance was set at p < 0.05.

Experimental animals
A total of 27 adult (12 weeks) male Sprague-Dawley rats (280–300g) obtained from Envigo (Hsd:Sprague Dawley® SD, Indianapolis, IN) were randomly assigned to a control, uninjured group or to C2SH surgery and followed for 3 or 21 days afterwards (3DSH and 21DSH, respectively). All procedures were conducted in accordance with the American Physiological Society’s Animal Care Guidelines and were approved by the Institutional Animal Care and Use Committee at the Mayo Clinic. Animals were housed individually in cages under a 12-h light/dark cycle with ad libitum access to food and water. Animals were anesthetized with ketamine (90 mg/kg) and xylazine (10 mg/kg) via intraperitoneal injection for all experimental procedures.

Phrenic motor neuron labeling
Labelling of the PhMN pool was achieved by injecting two 10 µl injections of 0.2% Alexa Fluor 488-conjugated cholera toxin subunit B solution (CTB-488) (
C22841
, Thermo Fisher Scientific, Waltham, MA) bilaterally into the intrapleural space as previously described (
Mantilla et al., 2013a
;
Mantilla et al., 2009
;
Rana et al., 2019
;
Rana et al., 2017
). Briefly, the awake animal was lightly restrained and a 20-gauge Hamilton syringe (7731–10, Hamilton Company, Reno, NV) was used to inject CTB-488 between the 7th and 8th ribs. CTB-488 was delivered 5 days prior to the terminal time experiment to allow ample time for labelling of the PhMN pool.

Assessment of diaphragm muscle activity
Chronic diaphragm muscle EMG activity was assessed in C2SH animals using a pair of electrodes that were threaded into the mid-costal region of the diaphragm bilaterally, as previously described (
Gransee et al., 2013
;
Mantilla et al., 2013a
;
Mantilla et al., 2011
;
Rana et al., 2017
). Briefly, a midline laparotomy was performed to expose the inferior surface of the diaphragm and a pair of electrodes made from insulated stainless steel fine wire (AS631, Cooner Wire Inc., Chatsworth, CA) with a ~3 mm exposed region was placed into each hemi-diaphragm muscle with an inter-electrode distance of ~3 mm. The electrode pair was secured in place using a surgical knot at the muscle surface, looped intra-abdominally, tunneled sub-cutaneously, externalized and secured in the dorsum of the animal. Animals were allowed to recover prior to C2SH surgery for at least 3 days in order to avoid possible laparotomy-induced inhibition of neural activity of the diaphragm, which peaks ∼6–8 h after laparotomy and returns to baseline by ~48 h (
Dureuil et al., 1986
;
Ford et al., 1983
).
Baseline diaphragm EMG activity was recorded at 1 day prior to injury to evaluate technical success in EMG placement, and at 3 days postoperatively to confirm absence of EMG after C2SH. For every session, the EMG signal for each pair of diaphragm muscle electrodes was differentially amplified (gain: 2000x) and band-pass filtered (20–1000Hz) using an analog amplifier (Model 2124, DATA Inc.). The signal was digitized using a data acquisition board (National Instruments, Austin, TX) with sampling frequency of 2000 Hz and recorded using a custom-made program (LabView 8.2, National Instrument). The root mean square (RMS) amplitude of the EMG signal was calculated over a 50-ms window. Peak RMS (RMS
peak
) was determined from the EMG signal.
Diaphragm EMG activity was recorded during eupneic breathing (~2 min). RMS
peak
EMG amplitude was averaged during the entire 120 s exposure for eupnea. Spontaneous sighs were identified during the eupneic recording period with their characteristic dual-phasic burst, large amplitude and post-sigh apneic period.

Spinal Hemisection
Details of the C2SH surgical procedure have been previously published (
Gransee et al., 2015
;
Mantilla et al., 2007
;
Mantilla et al., 2018
;
Miyata et al., 1995
;
Prakash et al., 1999
). Under sterile conditions, a bilateral dorsal C2 laminectomy was performed, and the right half of the spinal cord was sectioned lateral to the dorsal fissure, thus transecting only the ventral and lateral funiculi, while preserving the dorsal funiculus on the side of C2SH. In order to verify completeness of C2SH, absence of ipsilateral diaphragm EMG activity was confirmed under anesthesia at the time of surgery and 3 days post-C2SH (3DSH). Previous studies by our group have evaluated the extent of histological damage following unilateral C2SH (
Mantilla et al., 2014a
;
Miyata et al., 1995
;
Sieck and Mantilla, 2009
). The C2SH injury consistently results in damage to the ventral and lateral columns at C2 resulting in absence of ipsilateral diaphragm EMG activity at C2SH 3D during eupneic breathing. Thus, a functional outcome was used to verify completeness of C2SH in the present study.

RNAscope in situ Hybridization
At the terminal experiment, animals were anesthetized and euthanized by exsanguination. The cervical spinal cord was promptly excised and placed in freezing isopentane and stored at −80ºC until sectioning. Subsequently, coronal (10 µm thick) sections were placed on slides (SuperFrost) and stored at −80ºC until further processing. The phrenic motor pool is usually found in ~20 of these coronal sections and 3–4 sections were stereologically selected (~100 µm apart) to sample ~50 PhMN containing the midnuclear portion of the motor neuron soma, per animal on each side. Additional sections were sampled as needed to achieve the desired number of PhMNs.
In situ
detection of AMPA and NMDA mRNA targets was performed using RNAscope® assay as previously described (
Rana et al., 2019
). Briefly, probe-Rn-Gria2-O2 (Cat# 508371, Accession No:
AF164344.1
Advanced Cell Diagnostics, Newark, CA, USA) was used to label Gria2 mRNA encoding the GluR2 subunit of AMPA receptors. Probe-Rn-Grin1-C3 (Cat# 317021-C3, Accession No:
NM_001270602
Advanced Cell Diagnostics) was used to label Grin1 mRNA encoding the obligatory NR1 subunit of NMDA receptors. The Gria2 and Grin1 subunits have previously been verified as being highly expressed in rat PhMNs (
Mantilla et al., 2012
;
Rana et al., 2019
,
Gransee, 2017
#14986). The manual multiplex fluorescent assay was performed using the Fluorescent Multiplex Reagent Kit (Cat# 320850, Advanced Cell Diagnostics) and manufacturer recommended protocol for fresh frozen samples, with some modifications as previously described (
Rana et al., 2019
). Importantly, probe conjugation with fluorescent targets was performed using the Amp-4 AltB combination, thus labeling Gria2 and Grin1 with Atto 550 and Atto647, respectively. Tissue was counterstained with DAPI and cover-slipped with ProLong Gold Antifade Mountant (Cat#
P36934
, Thermo Fisher Scientific, Waltham, MA). Slides were stored at 4ºC till imaged. Imaging was conducted within one week of hybridization to avoid degradation of fluorescent signal.

Confocal Imaging and Analysis
Spinal cord sections were imaged using a confocal microscope (Nikon Eclipse A1R, Nikon Instruments Inc., Melville, NY) equipped with A1 detection filters 450/50, 535/50,600/50 + 685/70 and interlock with four diode lasers (405 nm, 488 nm, 561 nm, and 640 nm). A 40x Plan Fluor objective (NA 1.30) was used to obtain all images (12-bit, 1024 × 1024 pixel array) with a 0.5 μm step size. Imaging parameters were selected by setting background as less than 10% of the dynamic range and preventing saturation of mRNA transcripts.
Retrogradely-labelled PhMNs with a distinct mid nuclear section with a visible nucleolus were selected for analyses of mRNA transcript. Quantitative analysis of mRNA transcripts in individually identified PhMN cell bodies was performed on the FIJI platform (ver. 2.0.0, RRID:SCR_002285, National Institute of Health, Bethesda, MD) using previously described method (
Rana et al., 2020a
). Briefly, maximum intensity projection images were obtained from the confocal z-stack. Integrated intensities and area of 20 discrete individual mRNA transcripts were measured, along with average background intensity per pixel. These values were used to obtain total number of transcripts in the region of interest as outlined by CTB labelled PhMN soma and superimposed on channels containing AMPA and NMDA mRNA transcript signal.
Additional morphometric analyses were performed for each PhMN, as previously described (
Fogarty et al., 2018
;
Issa et al., 2010
;
Mantilla et al., 2018
;
Prakash et al., 2000
;
Prakash et al., 1993
,
1994
;
Rana et al., 2019
). Somal surface areas and volume of motor neuron somata were estimated for a prolate spheroid by measuring the major and minor axes in the midnuclear section. Estimated mRNA transcripts density was obtained by normalizing total number of mRNA transcripts per probe to normalized to optical slice volume for the mid-nuclear motor neuron section. This assumes a comparable density of mRNA across the motor neuron. Experimenter was blinded to experimental group for all analyses. Images were converted to 8-bit in NIS Elements for presentation only. No thresholding or post-imaging processing was applied for any images used in analysis.

Statistical Analysis
All statistical evaluations were performed using JMP statistical software (version 14.0, SAS Institute Inc., Cary, NC). The study statistical design was powered to consider the across subject and within subject variance in order to detect a 15% difference at p<0.05. Accordingly, we included 6 animals per experimental group and sampled ~50 PhMNs per animal per side using a stereological approach. For measurements repeated for the same animal (e.g., mRNA transcript density and total number of mRNA transcripts per PhMN), PhMN somal surface area, experimental group and side were included as model variables. An additional model was generated after grouping PhMNs into tertiles according size for each animal. PhMN size generally reflects motor unit type and thus would be recruited differentially to accomplish the various motor behaviors by the diaphragm muscle (
Fournier and Sieck, 1988
;
Mantilla et al., 2010
;
Mantilla and Sieck, 2011
;
Seven et al., 2014
;
Sieck, 1988
;
Sieck, 1994
;
Sieck et al., 2013
;
Sieck and Fournier, 1989
). Accordingly, PhMNs in the lower tertile would be recruited first to accomplish lower force ventilatory behaviors, followed by PhMNs in the middle tertile to accomplish higher force ventilatory behaviors such as sighing or breathing against an occluded airway. Finally, PhMNs in the upper tertile would be recruited last to accomplish higher force non-ventilatory behaviors such as sneezing or other expulsive behaviors. Normality of the distribution was assessed using the Shapiro-Wilk test within each animal. Outliers were identified for each animal using an outlier box plot. No data was excluded from the analysis.
Using the mixed linear model, statistical significance was established at the 0.05 level and adjusted for any violation of the assumption of sphericity in repeated measures using the Greenhouse-Geisser correction. When appropriate,
post hoc
analyses were conducted using Tukey-Kramer honestly significant difference (HSD).

Animals
Experiments were conducted on 79 adult, male Sprague-Dawley rats (11-12 weeks of age, initial body weight ~350 g, Colony 217, ENVIGO) housed in a temperature and light-controlled environment (12-hour light/dark cycles) with food and water
ad libitum
. All experimental protocols were approved by the Institutional Animal Care and Use Committee at the University of Florida. Eight weeks after C2 hemisection surgery (C2Hx), rats were randomly assigned to groups and exposed to 28 consecutive days of: 1) normoxia (Nx28); 2) daily AIH (dAIH28), 3) mild CIH (IH28-5/5); and 3) moderate CIH (IH28-2/2). Experimental groups were: 1) intact+Nx28 (n=8); 2) intact+dAIH28 (n=10); 3 intact+IH28-5/5 (n=10); 4) intact+IH28-2/2 (n=10); 5) C2Hx+Nx28 (n=9); 6) C2Hx+dAIH28 (n=8); 7) C2Hx+IH28-5/5 (n=12); and 8) C2Hx+IH28-2/2 (n=12). Procedures used here were the same as described earlier (
Ciesla et al., 2021
), with the exceptions of the specific tissues studied and details of the analytical procedures.

Cervical hemisection (C2Hx)
Anesthesia, C2Hx and follow-up animal care were performed as previously described (
Fuller et al., 2008
;
Gonzalez-Rothi et al., 2015
). Briefly, anesthesia was induced with 3.5% isoflurane (in 100% O2) and maintained at 2-2.5% isoflurane (in 100% O2) via a nose cone throughout surgery; anesthetic depth was verified by the absence of toe pinch and palpebral responses. Body temperature was maintained at 36.5–37.5°C with a water heating pad. Artificial tears (Rugby, NDC 0536-1086-91) were applied. Nails were clipped from forelimbs and hind limbs to minimize scratching injuries. The surgical site was shaved and cleaned (chlorhexidine scrub, 58829-140-01, First Priority, Inc., Elgin, IL), and the C2 cervical spinal laminae exposed by making a dorsal incision on the neck and dissecting the muscles. Following C2 laminectomy and durotomy, the left C2 spinal cord was hemisected caudal to the C2 dorsal roots with a micro-knife . A gap (~1 mm) at the hemisection site was created by aspiration. At this time, C2Hx visualization showed anatomically complete lesions (absent white and gray matter from the left lateral edge to the spinal midline). The dura was closed (9-0 ethilon nylon suture), the overlaying muscles were sutured with 3-0 Polysorb absorbable suture, and skin was closed with 9mm stainless steel wound clips. Each rat received post-operative care including pain management (buprenorphine, 0.03 mg/kg, s.c., Hospira, IL; and meloxicam, 2 mg/kg, s.q. Portland, ME) given at 12 hour intervals for 2 days post-surgery. Rats received lactated Ringer’s solution (5 ml 2x/day, s.q.) and were fed manually with a nutritional supplement (Diet Gel Boost; Clear H
2
O; Westbrook, ME) until volitional drinking and eating was once again adequate.

Intermittent Hypoxia Protocols
Intermittent hypoxia protocols used in this study were described previously (
Ciesla et al., 2021
;
Gonzalez-Rothi et al., 2021
). Each gas mixture was delivered by to the rat’s home cage via programmable mass flow controllers; the mass flow controller system mixed gases as needed to achieve the desired oxygen concentrations at a constant flow (Therapeutiq, Kansas City, MO; cage volume = 4.5 L; total gas flow rate = 16 L/min per cage). Rats were housed in their cages during the course of exposures (28 days) with free access to food and water, starting 8 weeks post-C2Hx. Intermittent hypoxia protocols were administered during the light (rest) phase. Gases were filtered for microparticles and bacteria using high purity compressed air-filters (Parker-Hannifin, Cleveland, OH) and humidified to ~30-50% relative humidity with Nafion Fuel Cell Humidifiers (PermaPure, Lakewood, NJ) connected to a circulating water bath. The normoxia group received continuous gas flow of 21% O2 for 8-hrs per day. Rats assigned to the daily AIH (dAIH28) groups received 10, 5-min episodes of 10.5% O2, alternating with 5-min normoxic intervals, for a total of 1.5-hrs/day between 8 and 10 am. Rats assigned to IH28-5/5 groups received 5-min episodes of 10.5% O2 with 5-min normoxic intervals for a total of 8-hrs/day (6 hypoxic episodes per hour for 8-hrs, 48 episodes per day) between 8 am and 4 pm each day. The 5-min hypoxia/normoxia protocols results in 6 hypoxic episodes per hour, approximating clinical criteria for mild sleep apnea (
American Academy of Sleep Medicine, 1999
;
Young et al., 2008
). Rats assigned to IH28-2/2 groups received 2-min episodes of 10.5% O2 with 2-min normoxic intervals for a total duration of 8-hrs/day (8-hrs; 120 episodes per day), between 8 am and 4 pm. This protocol results in 15 hypoxic episodes per hour, equivalent to clinical diagnostic criteria for moderate sleep apnea (
American Academy of Sleep Medicine, 1999
;
Young et al., 2008
).

Tissue Histology and Analysis
The day after the final intermittent hypoxia or sham normoxia exposure, rats were perfused intracardially during the light phase with cold 0.1M phosphate buffer saline (PBS), followed by paraformaldehyde (4% paraformaldehyde w/v in 0.1M PBS, pH 7.4). Brainstems and spinal cords were harvested, post-fixed overnight in paraformaldehyde (4% paraformaldehyde w/v in 0.1M PBS, pH 7.4) and cryoprotected at 4°C in 20% sucrose solution in 0.1M PBS for 3 days, followed by 30% sucrose solution in 0.1M PBS for 3 days.
In addition to visual confirmation of the completeness of C2Hx at the time of injury, we further verified C2Hx completeness via histochemistry on fixed tissues. Paraffin-embedded cervical spinal segments (C1-C3) were cut in 7 μm transverse sections, mounted on positively-charged slides (Fisherbrand, Fisher Scientific, Pittsburgh, PA), and dried overnight. Sections were stained with Luxol Fast Blue and cresyl violet. Sections were deparaffinized by heating at 60°C for 20-min and then submerged 3x in xylene (5-min each time). Sections were rehydrated by graded alcohol (100%-70%) for 2-min each and stained overnight using Luxol Fast Blue (0.1 g Luxol Fast Blue in 100 mL of 95% ethanol and 0.5 mL 10% acetic acid). The following day, tissue sections were rinsed with 95% ethanol for 2-min, and then distilled water for 5-min. Differentiation was achieved by dipping the tissue in 0.5% lithium carbonate and 70% ethanol, then rehydrated with distilled water for 5-min. Tissues were placed in 0.1% cresyl violet for 15-min and rinsed by dipping tissue into distilled water twice. Tissue was dehydrated through graded alcohol (70–100%) for 1-min, cleared in Histoclear twice for 2-min (National Diagnostics, Atlanta, GA) and cover-slipped (Eukitt, Electron Microscope Science, PA). Injury sites were imaged using bright field at 10x zoom (BZ-×710, Keyence Co., Osaka, Japan). Completeness of C2Hx was verified in all sections by absence of tissue from midline to the lateral border (data not shown).
Brainstems were sectioned in transverse plane (40 μm thickness) using a freezing microtome (Leica SM 200R, Buffalo Grove, IL). Sectioned tissues were stored in antifreeze solution at −20°C until processed (30% glycerol, 30% ethylene glycol, 40% 0.1 M PBS, pH 7.4). A total of 6 medulla sections were sampled, 6 sections apart (240 μm between consecutive samples), and stained for serotonin (5-HT) and neurons (NeuN). Free-floating sections were washed with 0.1M PBS (pH 7.4) and incubated in heat induced epitope retrieval (TissuePro, cat#: HIER01-32R) for 30-min at 85°C. Tissues were washed with 0.1M PBS-Triton (0.1%, pH 7.4) and incubated in a blocking solution (5% normal donkey serum, NDS, GeneTex) in 0.1M PBS-Triton (0.1%, pH 7.4) at room temperature for 60-min. Primary antibody staining was performed by incubating tissue sections in 5% NDS in 0.1M PBS-Triton (0.1%, pH 7.4) with anti-5-HT (1/2000, rabbit serum, Immunostar #20080) and anti-NeuN (1/500, mouse serum, Millipore MAB377) at 4°C overnight. Tissues without primary antibody were also incubated overnight as controls. Tissue sections were washed with 0.1M PBS-Triton (0.1%, pH 7.4) the next day. Secondary antibody staining was performed by incubating sections in 5% NDS in 0.1M PBS-Triton (0.1%, pH 7.4) with secondary antibodies conjugated to Alexa Fluor® 594 (donkey anti-rabbit 594; 1:500, Invitrogen, Ref#A11055) and Alexa Fluor® 488 (donkey anti-mouse 488; 1/500, Invitrogen, Ref#A21202) in a dark box at room temperature for 2-hrs. Tissues without secondary antibody were also incubated as controls. We identified antibody binding in the caudal raphe nuclei as a positive control to verify antibody specificity. Sections were washed with 0.1M PBS-Triton (0.1%, pH 7.4), mounted on positively charged slides (Fisherbrand, Fisher Scientific, Pittsburgh, PA) and allowed to dry overnight. Slides were cover-slipped with VectaShield Antifade Hard Set Mounting Medium (Cat#:H-1400). Since immunohistochemical identification of serotonin can be affected by tissue fixation (
Clements and Beitz, 1985
), and the 5HT antibody used in this study detects antigen 5HT conjugated with paraformaldehyde, all rats were perfused under comparable conditions (4% paraformaldehyde in 1x PBS solution).

Image Acquisition
All immunofluorescently labeled tissue sections (transverse, 40 μm thickness) were imaged using an epifluorescent microscope with 20x magnification using the sectioning module with a 2D pinhole setting of 6, resulting in clear, high-resolution “confocal-like” images. (Keyence BZ-X700, Keyence Corporation of America, Itasca, IL). No black balance or binning was performed. We optimized our acquisition parameters such that the background intensities are ~5% of the dynamic range with minimal (<0.1%) saturation for the positively labeled areas. A Texas Red filter was used for 5-HT (OP-87765) and a GFP filter was used for NeuN (OP-87763). Exposure times of 1/60 seconds for 5-HT and 1/2.3 seconds for NeuN were used for imaging serotonin immunofluorescence around hypoglossal neurons. One image was taken on the left side (ipsilateral) and one on the right side (contralateral) resulting in two images per tissue section and ~12 total images per animal (~6 left, ~6 right). Medullas were marked prior to tissue sectioning to ensure accurate side determination during imaging and analyses.

Serotonin Immunofluorescence Analysis
Serotonin immunofluorescence was quantified in each image using a custom MATLAB (MathWorks, Natick, MA, USA) code as described previously (
Ciesla et al., 2021
). Local background intensities within each image were calculated using a running-window median filter and were subtracted from the raw pixel intensities to obtain the background-subtracted intensities. We performed our analyses on the background-subtracted intensities. Images were binarized using a custom adaptive threshold algorithm in MATLAB as previously described (
Allen et al., 2019
;
Ciesla et al., 2021
;
Seven et al., 2018
). An adaptive threshold was calculated by constructing a pixel intensity histogram from the image. Pixel intensity above a fixed percentile across all groups was selected as the threshold to account for animal-to-animal and image-to-image differences in signal and background intensities. The images were binarized using the automated algorithm to identify the serotonin-positive areas. Two investigators compared the identified serotonin structures with the original image to ensure the accuracy of identification. Automatically identified structures significantly matched investigator-based analysis. Investigators remained blinded to injury status and intermittent hypoxia exposure protocol throughout analyses.
Regions containing NeuN labeled XII motor neurons were selected for analysis based on their size and well-known anatomical location (
Krammer et al., 1979
;
Paxinos and Watson, 1998
). The MATLAB code first displayed green to identify motor neurons. A region of interest was selected, outlining the hypoglossal motor pool based on medulla level in reference to the obex, central canal and 4
th
ventricle, creating a polygon shape that encompassed all observed NeuN positive hypoglossal neurons >19 μm in diameter (
McClung and Goldberg, 1999
;
Rukhadze et al., 2010
). MATLAB code was then used to identify serotonin immunopositive pixels within this region of interest. In this report, we define the caudal XII nucleus as the region containing XII motor neurons from obex to 1.6 mm rostral to obex. The hypoglossal column is defined by all hypoglossal neurons, including pre-hypoglossal neurons, from obex to 3.5 mm rostral to obex. We report serotonergic innervation of both regions but emphasize the caudal hypoglossal nuclei in this paper since this region contains the motor neurons most involved in maintaining upper airway patency (e.g. genioglossus;
Cori et al., 2018
;
Krammer et al., 1979
).
We observed serotonin-immunopositive boutons (i.e. varicosities) and fibers. Since this analysis cannot differentiate between serotonin boutons
versus
fibers, we identified “serotonin structures,” defined as independent serotonin positive regions larger than 4 contiguous pixels; each structure was separated by at least 1 pixel. Using these definitions, we quantified: 1) structure number, 2) area per structure, 3) total immunopositive area, and 4) staining intensity per structure (based on fluorescence intensity).
The number of structures was determined by counting the number of immuno-positive serotonin structures per tissue section and averaging the number of immunolabeled structures per rat. The area per structure was determined by the number of contiguous pixels defining each structure. Pixel numbers were multiplied by the aspect ratio of pixel per micron (pixel dimensions: 0.377 μm × 0.377 μm) to determine the area per structure using a representative image from each tissue section, and then averaged to obtain the average area of each immunolabeled structure per rat. The total area of serotonin-positive immunolabeling was calculated by multiplying the structure number by area per structure in a representative image from each tissue section, and then averaged to obtain total serotonin immunolabeling area within the XII motor nucleus per rat. Although we do report staining intensity per structure, we acknowledge limitations in making inferences about serotonin concentration based on these measurements (
Fritschy, 2008
;
Matos et al., 2010
). The fluorescence intensity of each immunolabeled structure was determined within a representative image from each tissue section and averaged per rat. All intensity measurements were normalized to the maximum possible intensity (i.e. 65536).

Statistics
Statistical inferences were made using JMP 11.0 software (SAS Institute, Cary, NC). All computed values were first averaged within the image to obtain a value for the image. Then, image values were averaged for each animal, which was used for statistical calculations. Serotonin immunofluorescence was analyzed using a mixed model with a repeated measures design. Independent variables were intermittent hypoxia protocol (Nx28, dAIH28, IH28-5/5, IH28-2/2), injury (intact vs. C2Hx), and side relative to injury (ipsilateral vs. contralateral as a repeated measure). Due to the large number of comparisons within the mixed model, we were concerned that significance would be hidden within intact and C2Hx groups. To avoid type 2 statistical errors, the intact and C2Hx groups were analyzed separately. In uninjured rats, we averaged left and right sides and ran a one-way ANOVA with intermittent hypoxia protocol as the independent variable. In C2Hx groups, we ran a two-way repeated measures ANOVA with the independent variables being intermittent hypoxia protocol (Nx28, dAIH28, IH28-5/5, and IH28-2/2) and side (ipsilateral vs. contralateral as a repeated measure).
In the results, we report significant interactions for each for each outcome measure for serotonin immunofluorescence at the XII motor nucleus. A significance level of 0.05 was set for all statistical comparisons. p-values, F ration, and degrees of freedom (DF) are reported for Mixed Models. When significant differences were observed, individual comparisons were made with Fisher Least Significance Difference (LSD)
post hoc
tests. All data are displayed as mean ± standard error of the mean.
